'''D'Jais Bar & Grill''' is a popular<ref name="NYT Special">{{cite news|last=Special to the New York Times|title=Jersey town shuts bars early - and stirs debates|newspaper=New York Times|page=34|date=June 22, 1986}}</ref> dance club and restaurant in [[Belmar, New Jersey]]. It has been called a landmark, "infamous", and one of the most famous bars along the [[Jersey Shore]].<ref name=living>{{cite news|last=Glickson|first=G|title=If you're thinking of living in Belmar|newspaper=New York Times|date=6 September 1992|pages=R5}}</ref><ref name=bite>{{cite news|last=DeMasters|first=Karen|title=By the beach, a club and a club sandwich|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/08/18/nyregion/quick-bite-belmar-by-the-beach-a-club-and-a-club-sandwich.html |newspaper=New York Times|date=18 August 2002|pages=NJ12}}</ref>

==Location and Name==
D'Jais Bar & Grill is located at 1801-1805 Ocean Avenue, a street which runs north and south along the Belmar coastline. It is on the west side of the street, and the front entrance faces the beach and boardwalk. According to Frank Sementa, who has been the owner since 1979, the name "D'Jais" comes from the childhood nickname of the first owner of the club, Dominick Joseph DiSalvo, who was called "DJ".<ref name="video">{{cite web|last=The Borough of Belmar New Jersey|title=Home movie of Belmar from the Summer of ‘59 Surfaces on YouTube|url=http://belmar.com/tourism-news/2009/05/home-movie-of-belmar-from-the-summer-of-59-surfaces-on-youtube/|work=Belmar|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=7 February 2011}}</ref>

==History==
[[File:djafter sm.jpg|left|250px|Southern view from the ocean side.]] D'Jais was established in 1959. Locally, it has been called the most popular bar in town,<ref name="Cariello; Cariello, p. 89">Cariello; Cariello, p. 89.</ref> and was busy from the start.<ref name=video /> D'Jais is still a popular spot <ref name="living"/> and has been called a "Jersey shore institution for young people".<ref name="bite"/> During the 1970s, D'Jais was also regular spot for [[Bruce Springsteen]], who also took part in softball games and picnics hosted by the establishment,<ref name=sanford>{{cite book|last=Sandford|first=Christopher|title=Springsteen: point blank|year=1999|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-80921-7|pages=214–215}}</ref> as well as singer and guitarist [[Bobby Bandiera]].<ref name=Douglass>{{cite book|last=Douglass College|title=New Jersey folklife.|year=1988|publisher=American Studies Dept., Rutgers University|location=Ch. 13, p. 44}}</ref> During that era, it was considered "the most celebrated of the bars across from the boardwalk", and was popularized for offering five six-ounce pilsner glasses of beer for a dollar.<ref>Blum, p.36.</ref> Local bands also played at the venue during the 70s, including [[Holme (band)|Holme]], whose members included Bobby Bandiera, Frank Sementa, and Kip Conner.<ref>Sandford, p. 215.</ref><ref name=lively>{{cite news|last=Ames|first=L|title=The lively world of club circuit rock|newspaper=New York Times|date=7 May 1978|location=NJ28}}</ref><ref name=cheap>{{cite news|last=Mikle|first=J |title=Cheap concerts, free festivals could be music to your ears<!--|accessdate=6 February 2011--> |newspaper=Asbury Park Press (online)|date=14 June 2009}}</ref> It was purchased by Sementa, Luddecke, and Conner in 1979. They converted it from a bar famous for its live bands and cheap beer to a trendy dance club with a DJ, theme nights, and a party atmosphere.<ref name=bite/><ref name="PR2013">{{cite news |last=Satore |first=Bielat |date=18 July 2013 |title= Bielat Santore & Company's "WHO'S WHO in the Restaurant Industry. One of the Jersey Shore's most popular bars is open for the Summer. |url=http://www.benzinga.com/pressreleases/13/07/p3765027/bielat-santore-companys-whos-who-in-the-restaurant-industry |publisher= PRWeb|page=|accessdate= 15 May 2016}}</ref>

In 1984, Monmouth County officials adopted a uniform 2&nbsp;am closing time to discourage patrons from driving to other towns to find bars open later; however in 1986, D'Jais began closing at 12&nbsp;am.<ref name=stirs>{{cite news|last=Staff|title=Jersey Town Shut Bars Early- and stirs debate|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/22/nyregion/jersey-town-shuts-bars-early-and-stirs-debate.html |accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 June 1986}}</ref> Around 1990, Sementa added the restaurant to the site.<ref name=autogenerated1>Newspaper publication date 2002, stated "12 years ago": ''2002 - 12 = 1990'' per [[WP:CALC|routine calculations]].</ref> In 2005, a study was conducted at the request of neighboring residents by the [[Alcoholic beverage control state|ABC]] board to analyze the bars operations and occupancy levels. The residents believed patrons of D'Jais had violated Quality of Life conditions.<ref>Lott, p. 1.</ref> Residents were cited as spotting multiple fights, as well as other disruptive behavior.<ref>Lott, p. 34.</ref>

===Restaurant and dance club===
The appearance of D'Jais has changed since the 1970s. The outdoor portion of the restaurant is covered by rooftop, and provides patrons with oceanview seating.<ref name=bite/> The interior features four full-sized bars, as well as one that sits upon the outside deck.<ref name=Corv/> During the summer, most nights D'Jais features a DJ and dance music. There are frequently theme nights and contests.<ref name=Corv/> On Monday nights in the summer, Holme, a New Jersey band whose popularity dates back to the 1970s, entertains the crowd.<ref name=cheap/><ref name=finale>{{cite news|last=Zedalis|first=J|title=Perfect forecast for finale season of surf and sun expected to end on a high note.|newspaper=Asbury Park Press|date=2 September 2005|author2=Alexander, A.|location=p. 1}}</ref>

==Notoriety==
D'Jais is considered a landmark dance club and restaurant,<ref>{{cite web|title=D'Jais Oceanview Bar & Cafe|url=http://jerseyshore.metromix.com/bars-and-clubs/dance_club/djais-oceanview-bar-and-belmar-lake-como/493896/content|work=[[Metromix]]|accessdate=7 February 2011}}</ref> and has been called many things, including "infamous" and "guido-central".<ref name=Corv>{{cite news|last=Corvino|first=Taylor|title=The D'Jais way The low down on this reputed Belmar club|url=http://jerseyshore.metromix.com/bars-and-clubs/article/the-djais-way/1985188/content|accessdate=7 February 2011|newspaper=[[Metromix]]|date=3 June 2010}}</ref> D'Jais was named the best overall party spot and ranked 4th out of 100 in the 100 Best Bars at the Shore by ''Fun New Jersey''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 100 Bars Down the NJ Shore|url=http://www.funnewjersey.com/upload_user/Best_New_Jersey_bars_and_Clubs/TOP_100_SHORE_BARS_NJ.HTM|work=Fun New Jersey|accessdate=7 February 2011}}</ref> The club has attracted sports celebrities such as [[Kim Clijsters]] and [[Brian Lynch (basketball)|Brian Lynch]].<ref name=break>{{cite news|last=Robbins|first=L.|title=After break and break up, Clijsters makes a fresh start|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0DEED61F3EF93AA1575BC0A9639C8B63&scp=1&sq=After%20break%20and%20break%20up,%20Clijsters%20makes%20a%20fresh%20start&st=cse|newspaper=New York Times|date=29 August 2005|location=F4}}</ref> Locally, it has been called the most popular bar in town,<ref name="Cariello; Cariello, p. 89"/> and a local hot spot.<ref name=gould>{{cite news |last1=Gould |first1=Joe |last2=McShane |first2=Larry |title=Crowds smaller at Belmar nightspot after uproar over mayor's comments |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/2008/07/19/2008-07-19_crowds_smaller_at_belmar_nightspot_after-1.html |accessdate=7 February 2011 |newspaper=[[NY Daily News]] |date=19 July 2008}}</ref>

==New Jersey Sand Castle Contest==
D'Jais is the lead sponsor of the annual New Jersey [[Sand art and play|Sand Castle]] contest at the 18th Avenue beach. This contest typically attracts over 350 entries and about 10,000 participants each year.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 24th Annual NJ Sandcastle Contest at Belmar's 18th Avenue Beach c(07/28/10)|url=http://www.djais.com/subindex.php?p=viewGalleryExt&gID=168&sID=10&mID=8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sun, Sandcastles and…Pirate’s Booty|url=http://www.njsandcastle.com/pressreleases_july20_2010.htm}}</ref>
D'Jais also participates in other local and regional charity events.<ref name=Bowman>{{cite news|last=Bowman|first=B.|title=Challenge in Avon to help military families.|newspaper=Asbury Park Press online archives|accessdate=6 February 2011|url=http://www.APP.com|date=16 July 2009}}</ref><ref name=art>{{cite news|last=Seidel|first=B.|title=Art News<!--|accessdate=6 February 2011--> |newspaper=Asbury Park Press (online)|date=3 October 2008}}</ref>

