{{Use British English|date=July 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Multiple issues| {{Refimprove|date=April 2017}} {{Original research|date=August 2017}} }} {{Infobox company | name = Entertainment Rights | logo = Entertainment Rights.png | type = [[Public company|Public]] | fate = Absorbed into [[DreamWorks Classics|Classic Media]] | successor = [[DreamWorks Classics]] | foundation = {{start date and age|1989}} | defunct = {{end date and age|2009}} | location_city = [[London]], [[England]] | location_country = [[United Kingdom]] | industry = Global media company | products = [[Children]] and [[family]] [[Children's television series|television programming]] | parent = [[Boomerang Media]] | homepage = }}
'''Entertainment Rights''' was a media company with international business in the production and sales of [[Children's television series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entertainmentrights.com/corporate/ |title=Corporate |publisher=Entertainment Rights |date= |accessdate=2011-11-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808043537/http://www.entertainmentrights.com/corporate/ |archivedate=8 August 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2017}} The business entity was first founded in 1989 as "Sleepy Kids". In 1999, the company was renamed "Entertainment Rights".<ref>{{cite web|title=Entertainment Rights Plc: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=645700|website=Bloomberg|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>
==History== In 1989, "Sleepy Kids" was founded by Martin and Vivien Schrager-Powell. It was created in order to produce ''[[Midnight Patrol: Adventures in the Dream Zone]]'' (Potsworth and Co. in the UK) a children's animated series. Schrager-Powell's business partner was [[Hanna-Barbera]]. Within months of the founding, Sleepy Kids became a public company. It produced ''[[Dr. Zitbag's Transylvania Pet Shop]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=UK: Making it Tough for Tots - Sleepy Kids.|url=http://www.managementtoday.co.uk/uk-making-tough-tots-sleepy-kids/article/409470|website=Management Today|accessdate=2011-11-15|date=1992-06-01}}</ref> and ''[[Budgie the Little Helicopter]]''.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}
Between 1998 and 1999, Sleepy Kids expanded. In December 1998, the company merged with [[Richard Digance|The Richard Digance Card Company]], Clipper Films and Ridgeway Films. In 1999, the company acquired [[Siriol Productions]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/skd-media-to-buy-out-carrington-productions/1223882.article |title=Skd Media To Buy Out Carrington Productions |publisher=Broadcast |date=1999-10-29 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Also in 1999, Sleepy Kids purchased Boom Boom (owner of ''[[Basil Brush]]''), Carrington Productions International (owner of the Ventureworld Films and ''[[Dr. Zitbag's Transylvania Pet Shop]]''.{{Citation needed|date=July 2014}}
Following these acquisitions, Sleepy Kids was renamed "SKD Media". In 2000, SKD Media was renamed "Entertainment Rights".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/skd-boosts-overseas-sales-profile/1225306.article |title=SKD boosts overseas sales profile |publisher=Broadcast |date=1999-11-26 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Entertainment Rights purchased the rights to programs from companies such as Link Entertainment (distributors for [[Woodland Animations]])<ref>{{cite web|last1=Waller|first1=Ed|title=Entertainment Rights buys Postman Pat creator|url=http://www.c21media.net/entertainment-rights-buys-postman-pat-creator/|website=C21Media|accessdate=1 November 2017|date=7 November 2001}}</ref> Varga London, Hibbert Ralph Entertainment, and [[Peter Maddocks|Maddocks Animation]] and Little Entertainment Company.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}}
In 2004, Entertainment rights acquired Tell-Tale Productions<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3650828.stm |title=Tweenies maker bought for £3.1m |publisher=BBC News |date=2004-09-13 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crisherentertainment.com/entertainment-rights-acquires-tell-tale-productions/ |title=Entertainment Rights acquires Tell-Tale Productions |publisher=Crisher Entertainment |date=2004-09-13 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref> and rights to most of the [[Filmation]] library from [[Sonar Entertainment]] (Hallmark).{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}}
At the end of 2004, Entertainment Rights employed 95 people.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}} In the 2005 financial year, Entertainment Rights' [[revenue]] was £12.4 million. The company bid for [[Chorion]] but the offer was rejected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://technologyweekly.mad.co.uk/Main/Home/Articles/0a3172d4201c47efbda8d9c815916ac1/Chorion-rejects-Entertainment-Rights-offer.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130707044420/http://technologyweekly.mad.co.uk/Main/Home/Articles/0a3172d4201c47efbda8d9c815916ac1/Chorion-rejects-Entertainment-Rights-offer.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-07-07 |title=Welcome to the new mad.co.uk |publisher=Technologyweekly.mad.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2013-05-31 }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2017}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/3453967.stm |title=Noddy owner rejects bid approach |publisher=BBC News |date=2004-02-03 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref>
In 2005, [[Siriol Productions]] came under new management. The company was renamed "[[Calon (TV production company)|Calon]]". Most of the rights to completed productions were kept by Entertainment Rights.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lianne Stewart |url=http://kidscreen.com/2005/08/01/siriol-20050801/#ixzz1Yj6FYh00 |title=Siriol heads south, and Lyons moves on |publisher=Kidscreen |date=2005-08-01 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref>
On 11 January 2007, Entertainment Rights acquired Classic Media for {{USD|210 million}} (£106.9 million). Before completion, both companies announced distribution and production agreements with [[Genius Products]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Genius Products announces long-term co-production and distribution agreements with Entertainment Rights PLC and Classic Media|url=http://www.geniusproducts.com/PressRelease.aspx?releaseid=207|website=Genius Products|publisher=Wayback Machine|accessdate=18 September 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928101213/http://www.geniusproducts.com/PressRelease.aspx?releaseid=207|archivedate=28 September 2007|date=8 January 2007}}</ref>
In December 2008, the company appointed of Deborah Dugan, former president of [[Disney Publishing Worldwide]], as its Chief Executive Officer (CEO). There had been financial instability within the company.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Katie|title=ER announces new CEO|url=http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/er-announces-new-ceo/035902|website=Licensing.biz|accessdate=2011-11-15|date=2008-12-08}}</ref>
By January 2009, the company had dismissed one third of its employees. The company's market value decreased from £267 million in March 2007 to £5.5 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/media/4163292/Three-companies-in-talks-to-buy-Entertainment-Rights.html |title=Three companies in talks to buy Entertainment Rights |publisher=Telegraph |date=2009-01-07|accessdate=2011-11-15 |location=London |first1=Amanda |last1=Andrews |first2=Ben |last2=Harrington}}</ref> By February 2009, six companies had requested to purchase Entertainment Rights.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Loveday|first1=Samantha|url=http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/six-bid-for-entertainment-rights/035716 |title=Six bid for Entertainment Rights |publisher=Licensing.biz |date=2009-01-26 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref> Also in February 2009, Entertainment Rights was fined £245,000 by the [[Financial Services Authority]] for failing to inform shareholders of "a potential $14 million earnings hit in a timely manner".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Loveday|first1=Samantha|url=http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/now-entertainment-rights-is-hit-with-fsa-fine/035717 |title=Now Entertainment Rights is hit with FSA fine |publisher=Licensing.biz |date=2009-01-23 |accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref>
On 1 April 2009, Entertainment Rights went into voluntary [[administration (law)|administration]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Daily Mail Reporter|title=Entertainment Rights is sold off|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/article-1166534/Entertainment-Rights-sold-off.html|website=This is Money|accessdate=2013-05-31|date=2009-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Chas Tang |url=http://entertainmentrightsplc.blogspot.co.uk/2009/08/entertainment-rights-plc-four-months-on.html |title=Entertainment Rights Plc - four months on|publisher=Entertainment Rights Shareholders Action |date=2009-08-10 |accessdate=2013-05-31}}</ref> On the same day, [[Boomerang Media]] announced it had acquired all of Entertainment Rights subsidiaries including Entertainment Rights itself, Big Idea and Classic Media. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Loveday|first1=Samantha|title=Boomerang Media acquires Entertainment Rights' subsidiaries|url=http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/boomerang-media-acquires-entertainment-rights-subsidiaries/035328|website=Licensing.biz|accessdate=2011-11-15|date=2009-01-23}}</ref> On May 11, 2009, Boomerang Media announced that the former U.K. and U.S. subsidiaries of Entertainment Rights would operate as a unified business under the name "Classic Media", while Big Idea would operate under its own name.<ref name="Tribbey">{{cite news|last1=Tribbey|first1=Chris|title=Classic Media Absorbs Subsidiaries|url=http://www.homemediamagazine.com/studios/classic-media-absorbs-subsidiaries-15704|accessdate=12 May 2009|work=Home Media Magazine|date=11 May 2009|language=en}}</ref> Boomerang Media was created by former owners of Classic Media until it was sold to Entertainment Rights in 2006.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}
In 2012, Classic Media was acquired by [[DreamWorks Animation]].<ref name=LATDWA>{{cite news|last=Verrier|first=Richard|title=DreamWorks Animation buys 'Casper,' 'Lassie' parent Classic Media|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jul/23/entertainment/la-et-ct-dreamworks-animation-20120722|accessdate=November 30, 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=July 23, 2012}}</ref> DreamWorks Animation was then acquired by [[NBCUniversal]] in 2016, thus [[Universal Pictures]] gaining the rights to most of Entertainment Rights' catalogue of works.
