{{dablink|Not to be confused with [[University of Oregon#Flux|''Flux'']], a student publication at the [[University of Oregon]].}} {{Infobox Magazine |title = Flux Magazine |image_file = FluxIssue3.jpg |image_size = 200px |editor = Jeff Kitts |publisher = Dennis Page |frequency = Bi-monthly |category = [[Video game|Gaming]], [[Music magazine]] |company = [[Harris Publications]] |founded = 1994 |firstdate = |finaldate = 1995 |country = United States |based = [[New York City]] |language = English |ISSN = 1074-5602 }}
'''''Flux''''' was a short-lived magazine in the mid-1990s which focused on music (mostly [[hard rock]] and [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]]), [[comic book]]s and [[video game]]s.
==History and profile== The magazine was [[bi-monthly]] and lasted for seven issues. The headquarters was in [[New York City]] and the publisher was [[Harris Publications]].<ref name=saga>{{cite web|title=Harris Publishing, Inc.|url=http://samuelsaguamediastuff.weebly.com/publishing-house.html|work=Samuel Saga's Media Stuff|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> It was presented as an edgier alternative to magazines such as [[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]] and [[GamePro]]. Notable recurring departments included "Don't Ever Do This," which offered explicit instructions for pranks and antisocial behavior, and "Babewatch," which was merely photos of attractive females from TV shows, movies, and comic books.
Amongst its editors was [[Dan Amrich]], who would go on to write for [[GamePro]] for several years under the moniker of Dan Elektro. Comics reviews were written by [[Christopher Golden]], who would later write comics himself, as well as horror and fantasy novels. The magazine folded in 1995.<ref name=saga/>
